---
import Header from '../components/Header.astro';
import Footer from '../components/Footer.astro';
---
<!doctype html>
<html lang="en">
  <head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8" />
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0" />
    <meta name="generator" content={Astro.generator} />
    <title>Schools of the Republic — A public library of America's school trust lands</title>
    <meta
      name="description"
      content="Schools of the Republic — a public library of America's school trust lands. Read the encyclopedia, find your state, map the architecture, audit the ledger."
    />
  </head>
  <body class="min-h-screen bg-slate-50 text-slate-900">
    <Header />
    <main class="mx-auto max-w-5xl p-4 sm:p-8">
      <section class="border-b border-slate-200 pb-10">
        <h1 class="text-4xl font-bold tracking-tight sm:text-5xl">
          Schools of the Republic
        </h1>
        <p class="mt-3 text-lg text-slate-600 sm:text-xl">
          A public library of America's school trust lands
        </p>
        <p class="mt-6 text-base font-medium text-slate-800 sm:text-lg">
          America gave land to its schools. This is the ledger of what happened next.
        </p>
        <div class="prose prose-slate mt-6 max-w-none">
          <p>
            In 1785, before the Constitution, the United States began setting aside public land
            for public schools. Some states turned that inheritance into permanent funds worth
            billions. Others sold it, raided it, or quietly let it disappear.
          </p>
          <p>
            This library is for inspecting what happened. The same fifty states appear across six
            rooms — read the history, find your state, map the architecture, audit the ledger,
            follow the case law, see where breaches hit the floor and where recovery has held.
            Every figure carries a confidence badge. Every blank cell is a deliberate signal.
          </p>
          <p>
            Start with your state, the national map, or the short guide to how the school-trust
            compact worked — and how it drifted.
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="mt-10" aria-label="Three doors">
        <ul class="grid grid-cols-1 gap-4 sm:grid-cols-3">
          <li class="rounded-lg border border-slate-200 bg-white p-5 shadow-sm transition hover:shadow">
            <a href="/start/" class="block">
              <p class="text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-wide text-slate-500">
                Start Here
              </p>
              <h2 class="mt-2 text-xl font-semibold tracking-tight text-blue-700 underline-offset-2 hover:underline">
                What are school trust lands?
              </h2>
              <p class="mt-3 text-sm text-slate-700">
                The 1785 land ordinance, the trust that followed, the drift, and how to read
                what's on this site. Ten minutes.
              </p>
            </a>
          </li>
          <li class="rounded-lg border border-slate-200 bg-white p-5 shadow-sm transition hover:shadow">
            <a href="/reading/" class="block">
              <p class="text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-wide text-slate-500">
                Find Your State
              </p>
              <h2 class="mt-2 text-xl font-semibold tracking-tight text-blue-700 underline-offset-2 hover:underline">
                Reading Room
              </h2>
              <p class="mt-3 text-sm text-slate-700">
                Every state has an entry. Read your state's full encyclopedia entry, or jump to
                its row in the Counting House and its polygon on the Atlas.
              </p>
            </a>
          </li>
          <li class="rounded-lg border border-slate-200 bg-white p-5 shadow-sm transition hover:shadow">
            <a href="/atlas/" class="block">
              <p class="text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-wide text-slate-500">
                See the National Pattern
              </p>
              <h2 class="mt-2 text-xl font-semibold tracking-tight text-blue-700 underline-offset-2 hover:underline">
                Atlas
              </h2>
              <p class="mt-3 text-sm text-slate-700">
                One map, four lenses. Era cohort, fund corpus, federal grant acreage,
                transparency status. The same fifty states answer four different questions.
              </p>
            </a>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <section class="mt-12" aria-label="Featured entry points">
        <h2 class="text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-wide text-slate-500">
          Featured entries
        </h2>
        <ul class="mt-4 grid grid-cols-1 gap-4 sm:grid-cols-3">
          <li class="rounded-lg border border-slate-200 bg-white p-5 shadow-sm">
            <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold tracking-tight">
              <a href="/reading/us-or/" class="text-blue-700 underline hover:text-blue-900">
                Oregon — the live test case
              </a>
            </h3>
            <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-slate-700">
              Strong constitutional architecture (1857), the Elliott State Forest decoupling
              (2017–2022), and the January 2026 Court of Appeals standing victory in
              <em>Advocates for School Trust Lands v. State of Oregon</em>. The case OASTL is
              currently litigating.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li class="rounded-lg border border-slate-200 bg-white p-5 shadow-sm">
            <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold tracking-tight">
              <a href="/reading/us-ut/" class="text-blue-700 underline hover:text-blue-900">
                Utah — the recovery case
              </a>
            </h3>
            <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-slate-700">
              Constituency rebuilt what architecture alone could not protect. The clearest
              national model for how a breached trust gets back on track.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li class="rounded-lg border border-slate-200 bg-white p-5 shadow-sm">
            <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold tracking-tight">
              <a href="/reading/us-ms/" class="text-blue-700 underline hover:text-blue-900">
                Mississippi — the lost inheritance
              </a>
            </h3>
            <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-slate-700">
              Section 16 history shows what depletion looks like when no recovery occurred.
              Sixteenth sections sold for as little as $1 per acre in the 1820s.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <section class="mt-10 rounded-md border border-slate-200 bg-white p-5 text-sm text-slate-700 shadow-sm">
        <p>
          Three rooms are live today: Reading Room, Atlas, Counting House. Three more open later
          in 2026: Records Room (curated primary sources, opening month 3), Court Room (case law
          and litigation, opening month 5–6), Breach &amp; Recovery (drift case studies, opening
          month 6–9).
        </p>
      </section>

      <section
        class="mt-10 rounded-lg border-l-4 border-amber-500 bg-amber-50 p-5 shadow-sm"
        aria-label="Why some numbers are blank"
      >
        <h2 class="text-base font-semibold tracking-tight text-amber-900">
          Why some numbers are blank
        </h2>
        <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-amber-900">
          You'll see "Awaiting State Disclosures" badges across this library. Twelve states
          publish complete school-trust accounting today. Thirty-eight don't. The Counting House
          makes that visible because that absence is the finding — not a defect of this site.
          Visible incompleteness with correction pathways is the fastest path to credibility, and
          it's the only way a public ledger of public trusts can earn its name.
        </p>
      </section>
    </main>
    <Footer />
  </body>
</html>
